From AIDS to Non-Communicable Diseases in Eight Key Points
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as cardiovascular diseases, strokes, cancer, diabetes, and chronic respiratory diseases, are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that tobacco use, sedentary behavior, poor diet, and excessive alcohol consumption increase the risk of premature death from NCDs.
Yet despite widespread knowledge of these risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It was in this context that the networks of alliances for NCDs met from December 9th to 11th at the second Global Forum on the Alliance for NCDs in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions to regulate NCDs, they should draw inspiration from the AIDS fight.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to lead interventions, and their unique form of mobilization has been essential in the progress made.
While the battle is not yet over, AIDS activists know that they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against NCDs could reverse this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, editor-in-chief of The Lancet, described the NCD community as being "in need of an electric shock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who will have the courage to deliver it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from AIDS activists.
As global attention focuses on preventing MNTs, those working to control avoidable diseases must draw inspiration from the ABCs of AIDS-fighting organizations.
The first letter that the MNT community must take note of is "A," for activism.
Anyone over 40 will surely remember images of AIDS activists participating in "die-in" protests at scientific conferences around the world.
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets, even shutting down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
Worldwide, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism should continue and serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Then, the MNT community must adopt a more bold approach to budgets - the "B" of the AIDS movement's strategy.
Civic organization and grassroots activism can mobilize initial energies, but organizing and maintaining a broad coalition requires money.
The AIDS movement was clear about this from the start and put pressure on securing resources to effectively support its awareness and accountability activities.
"C" represents coalitions: AIDS activism groups did not take long to understand that progress comes only with multiple supports.
Activists have linked people living with HIV to those with other concerns such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders with government powers to combine their perspectives and expertise.
The AIDS movement also realized that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential for spreading its support.
Thus, "D," the key determinant of success, consisted of 'drawing attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge.'
For example, lobbying educational leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make smart decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links were established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that played a key role in the AIDS crisis.
NCDs are no less isolated in their causality and also warrant a multi-sectoral approach to prevention.
Engagement - "E" - was what helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategically borrowing from the disability rights movement, which advocated the mantra "Nothing About Us Without Us," AIDS advocates demanded representation for existing organizations to address the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only United Nations agency with seats on its Board reserved for civil society representatives.
This standard is so deeply integrated into the AIDS movement that it would almost be unthinkable for an AIDS meeting to take place without civil society representation.
Disease prevention movements must also develop compelling narratives, and "F" - framing the issue - is essential for the AIDS community to gain political leadership support.
In particular, access to AIDS treatment has been framed as an issue of economic justice.
Framing the story this way led to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the point where more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are now on treatment.
An equally important framing of the issue for AIDS, which is very relevant to the MNT movement, is that of responsibility.
The AIDS community has worked hard to shift the focus more towards individual choices rather than attributing state responsibility for healthcare provision and the elimination of legal discrimination.
In the AIDS debate, gender - the 'G' of our movement - was a significant point.
HIV was initially seen as a 'gay disease', and gender identity rooted itself early in the DNA of the AIDS advocacy movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: just look at how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Gender, therefore, must become a focal point for MNT prevention efforts.
Finally, "H" - human rights - is the foundation of the AIDS response.
Campaigns have been launched against workplace discrimination, in schools, and in medical centers.
Strategic litigation has ensured legal equality.
The AIDS-fighting movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The MNT movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit unhealthy food advertising to children.
We could continue down the alphabet list of lessons learned from the fight against AIDS, but it seems appropriate to conclude on "H," given that human rights have provided the response to AIDS and should provide the response to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk of HIV.
The same is true for NCDs.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS activism movement clearly stated that this question was not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to avoidable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
MNT and AIDS communities can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The views expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
